Introduction

Universities are typically opaque, bureaucratic institutions. To be transparent to tax payers, many public schools, such as the University of North Carolina, openly report salary information. In this assignment, we will analyze this information from 2022 to answer pivotal questions that have endured over the course of time. The most recent salary data for UNC-Chapel Hill faculty and staff has already been downloaded in CSV format and titled Salary Data Export.csv.

To answer all the questions, you will need the R package tidyverse to make figures and utilize dplyr functions.

Data Information

Make sure the CSV data file is contained in the folder of your RMarkdown file. First, we start by using the read_csv function from the readr package found within the tidyverse. The code below executes this process by creating a tibble in your R environment named salary.

salary=read_csv("Salary Data Export.csv")

You will notice that the variable Hire_Date is recorded as a character. The following code will first modify the original dataset to change this to a date variable with the format mm/dd/yyyy. Then, we will remove the hyphens to create a numeric variable as yyyymmdd. Finally, in the spirit of tidyverse, we will convert this data frame to a tibble.

salary$Hire_Date=as.Date(salary$Hire_Date, format="%m/%d/%Y")
salary$Hire_Date=as.numeric(gsub("-","",salary$Hire_Date))
salary=as_tibble(salary)

Q6 (2 Points)

What is the average salary of employees in my department (Statistics and Operations Research)?

Code (1 Point):

avg_salary <- salary.final %>%
  group_by(Department) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(Salary)) %>%
  filter(Department == "Statistics and Operations Res")
avg_salary
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   Department                       mean
##   <chr>                           <dbl>
## 1 Statistics and Operations Res 125739.

Answer (1 Point): The average salary of employees working in the Statistics and Operations Research Department is $125,739.4

Q8 (4 Points)

What is the difference between the average age of employees in the History department who are professors, associate professors, or assistant professors and the average age of employees in my department who are professors, associate professors, or assistant professors?

Code (2 Points):

average_age_stor <- salary.final %>%
  filter(Department == "Statistics and Operations Res") %>%
  filter(Category %in% c("Professor", "Associate Professor", "Assistant Professor")) %>%
  summarize(mean(Age))
  
average_age_hist <- salary.final %>%
  filter(Department == "History") %>%
  filter(Category %in% c("Professor", "Associate Professor", "Assistant Professor")) %>%
  summarize(mean(Age))

average_age_hist - average_age_stor
##   mean(Age)
## 1  8.704878

Answer (2 Points): The average age of professors, associate professor, or assistant professors in the History department is about 8.7 years older than those in the STOR department. Note that I have assumed that we are looking for professors, associate professors, or assistant professors in the Category column and not the Title column. In my analysis, even distinguished professors are considered professors, which made sense to include in the type of analysis I was trying to do here.

Q9 (4 Points)

Based off the data in salary.final, create a grouped summary based off combinations of Department and Title. Call the new tibble dept_title_summary. Your summarized tibble, dept_title_summary, should report all of the following statistics with corresponding variable names in the following order.

  • n = number of employees for each combination

  • salary = average salary for each combination

  • age = average age for each combination

  • corr = correlation between the salary and age for each combination

In the process, make sure you use ungroup() with the pipe %>% to release the grouping so future work is no longer group specific. Also, the cor() can be used to calculate the correlation between two variables.

Following the creation of dept_title_summary, prove that your code worked by using head() to view the first 12 rows.

dept_title_summary = salary.final %>%
  group_by(Department, Title) %>%
  summarize(n = n(),
            salary = mean(Salary),
            age = mean(Age),
            corr = cor(x = Salary, y = Age)) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Department'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
head(dept_title_summary, 12)

high_avg_salary <- dept_title_summary %>%

Q11 (4 points)

Create a scatter plot using geom_point() along with fitted lines using geom_smooth with the argument method="lm" showing the linear relationship between average salary and the average age. Put the average age on the x-axis of your plot. For this plot, use the summarized data in dept_title_summary and exclude the combinations of Department and Title where there are less than 5 employees.

Following the plot, please explain what this plot suggests about the relationship between the average salary and the average age. Make reference to the figure and use descriptive adjectives (i.e.strong, weak, etc.) and terms (i.e.positive, negative, etc.) that are appropriate for discussing linear relationships.

Code and Figure (2 Points):

ggplot(data = dept_title_summary, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Answer (2 Points): From the above graph, we can see a positive relationship between age and salary. We can see that older people have a higher salary and with increase in age, salary also increases, as suggested by the blue line which has a positive slope. Most of the data is under the salary of $250k but we can also see a few outliers who have a really high salary compared to the rest of the demographic. It would be interesting, in my opinion, to see what the slope would look like if we were to remove the outliers, i.e, how much are the outliers swaying the line towards a positive slope, if at all?

Code and Figure: (4 Points):

# Selected Departments: Computer Science, Mathematics, Classics
comp_sci <- filter(dept_title_summary, Department == "Computer Science")
anesth <- filter(dept_title_summary, Department == "Anesthesiology")
anth <- filter(dept_title_summary, Department == "Anthropology")


ggplot(data = dept_title_summary) +
  geom_point(data = comp_sci, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary, color = "Computer Science")) +
  geom_point(data = anesth, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary, color = "Anesthesiology")) + 
  geom_point(data = anth, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary, color = "Anthropology")) + 
  geom_smooth(data = comp_sci, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary, color = "Computer Science"), se = FALSE, method = "lm") + 
  geom_smooth(data = anesth, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary, color = "Anesthesiology"), se = FALSE, method = "lm") + 
  geom_smooth(data = anth, mapping = aes(x = age, y = salary, color = "Anthropology"), se = FALSE, method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Answer (2 Points): For my analysis, I chose the department of Anesthesiology, Anthropology, and Computer Science. From a quick glance at the above graph, I can see that Anthropology has the largest positive slope followed by Computer Science and Anesthesiology has a negative slope. A positive value for the slope indicates that the average salary in the department is going up when age increases, while a negative value indicates a decrease in average salary with age. This observation was initially surprising to me because I expected Anesthesiologists to be making the most salary. Moreover, I expected Anthrolopolgy to have the lowest slope, but it proved to have a higher average salary than both the department of Computer Science and Anesthesiology.
